The {{nihongo|'''Kisaichi Maruyama Kofun'''|私市円山古墳|}} is a [[Kofun period]] [[kofun|Kofun]], located in the Kisaichi neighborhood of the city of [[:en:Ayabe, Kyoto|Ayabe, Kyoto]] in the [[Kansai region]] of [[Japan]]. The tumulus was designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1994.<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |url= https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/138977 |title=私市円山古墳|trans-title= Kisaichi Maruyama Kofun|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 20, 2020}}</ref>
==Overview== The Kisaichi Maruyama Kofun is a circular {{nihongo|''{{ill|Round Kofun|lt=enpun|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}-style tumulus with a diameter of 70 meters and a higher of 10 meters. It is located north of the center of the Fukuchiyama basin, in the central area of former [[Tanba Province]], on the central reaches of the [[Yura River (Japan)|Yura River]] at an elevation of 94 meters. It was discovered during a survey accompanying the construction of the [[Kinki Expressway]] (currently Maizuru Wakasa Expressway) in 1988. Until then, the existence of the tumulus was unknown. Due to this discovery, the construction method of the highway was changed from a cutting to a tunnel, and the Kofun was to be preserved. The mound had a three-tiered structure, and river stones of the Yura River were used as ''[[fukiishi]]''. Cylindrical ''[[haniwa]]'' were lined up on the flat part of the first and second tiers of the mound. In the [[archaeological excavation]], figurative ''haniwa'' and [[haji ware]] pottery. including house-shaped and armor-shaped examples were excavated. The [[burial chamber]] consisted of a central main room where the coffins were located, and sub-chambers to the north and south. Wooden coffins was found in the central and northern chambers, and [[grave goods]] such as armor, iron spearheads, iron swords and other weapons, agricultural tools, [[bronze mirror]]s, and jewelry were excavated, along with a quiver containing 38 arrows. From the quality and quantity of the grave goods, it is assumed that the central burial was that of a king who ruled the middlereaches of the Yura River in the mid-fifth century, and the northern burials were possibly siblings, parents and children. Only agricultural tools were sub-burial on the south side, which is presumed to have been that of a servant.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
When it was decided to preserve the tumulus, Ayabe City formulated the Kisaichi Maruyama tumulus environment improvement plan, re-laid the ''fukiishi'', lined up replicas of cylindrical ''haniwa'', and restored it as the "Maruyama Kofun Park" in May 1993.<ref name="Shiseki"/> In August 2014, heavy rains caused damage to the northwestern section of the mound, which collapsed over a width of 10 meters.
The tumulus is about a two-kilometer walk from [[Takatsu Station (Kyoto)|Takatsu Station]] on the [[JR West]] [[San'in Main Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
