==Overview== The Kisaichi Maruyama Kofun is a circular {{nihongo|''{{ill|Round Kofun|lt=enpun|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}-style tumulus with a diameter of 70 meters and a higher of 10 meters. It is located north of the center of the Fukuchiyama basin, in the central area of former {{ill|Tanba Province|en|Tanba Province|qid=Q954511|lt=Tanba Province|1=Tanba Province}}, on the central reaches of the {{ill|Yura River (Japan)|en|Yura River (Japan)|qid=Q11577617|lt=Yura River|1=Yura River (Japan)}} at an elevation of 94 meters. It was discovered during a survey accompanying the construction of the {{ill|Kinki Expressway|en|Kinki Expressway|qid=Q11638656|lt=Kinki Expressway|1=Kinki Expressway}} (currently Maizuru Wakasa Expressway) in 1988. Until then, the existence of the tumulus was unknown. Due to this discovery, the construction method of the highway was changed from a cutting to a tunnel, and the Kofun was to be preserved. The mound had a three-tiered structure, and river stones of the Yura River were used as ''[[fukiishi]]''. Cylindrical ''{{ill|Haniwa|en|Haniwa|qid=Q849376|lt=Haniwa|1=Haniwa}}'' were lined up on the flat part of the first and second tiers of the mound. In the [[archaeological excavation]], figurative ''haniwa'' and {{ill|Haji pottery|en|Haji pottery|qid=Q5639938|lt=Haji pottery|1=Haji pottery}} pottery. including house-shaped and armor-shaped examples were excavated. The [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]] consisted of a central main room where the coffins were located, and sub-chambers to the north and south. Wooden coffins was found in the central and northern chambers, and {{ill|Grave goods|en|Grave goods|qid=Q1399692|lt=Grave goods|1=Grave goods}} such as armor, iron spearheads, iron swords and other weapons, agricultural tools, {{ill|Bronze mirror|en|Bronze mirror|qid=Q1041984|lt=Bronze mirror|1=Bronze mirror}}s, and jewelry were excavated, along with a quiver containing 38 arrows. From the quality and quantity of the grave goods, it is assumed that the central burial was that of a king who ruled the middlereaches of the Yura River in the mid-fifth century, and the northern burials were possibly siblings, parents and children. Only agricultural tools were sub-burial on the south side, which is presumed to have been that of a servant.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
When it was decided to preserve the tumulus, Ayabe City formulated the Kisaichi Maruyama tumulus environment improvement plan, re-laid the ''fukiishi'', lined up replicas of cylindrical ''haniwa'', and restored it as the "Maruyama Kofun Park" in May 1993.<ref name="Shiseki"/> In August 2014, heavy rains caused damage to the northwestern section of the mound, which collapsed over a width of 10 meters.
The tumulus is about a two-kilometer walk from {{ill|Takatsu Station (Kyoto)|en|Takatsu Station (Kyoto)|qid=Q872015|lt=Takatsu Station|1=Takatsu Station (Kyoto)}} on the {{ill|West Japan Railway Company|en|West Japan Railway Company|qid=Q502125|lt=West Japan Railway Company|1=West Japan Railway Company}} {{ill|San&#39;in Main Line|en|San&#39;in Main Line|qid=Q1135170|lt=San&#39;in Main Line|1=San'in Main Line}}.<ref name="Shiseki"/>
